04618nam a22006375i 9780520975378DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2020014434  a97805209753787 a10.1525/97805209753782doi  a(DE-B1597)551594  a(OCoLC)1229160993  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aHV5840.C62bG453 2020 4aHV5840.C62bG453 2020eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a362.29/340951352231 aBartlett, Nicholas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRecovering Histories :bLife and Labor after Heroin in Reform-Era China /cNicholas Bartlett. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (222 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Toward a Phenomenology of Recovery -- t1. Mayhem on the Mountains: The Rush of Heroin's Arrival -- t2. Recovery as Adaptation: Catching Up to the Private Sector -- t3. Absence of a Future: Narrative, Obsolescence, and Community -- t4. Idling in Mao's Shadow: The Therapeutic Value of Socialist Labor -- t5. A Wedding and Its Afterlife: Relationships, Recovery -- t6. "From the Community": Civil Society Ambitions and the Limits of Phenomenology -- tEpilogue -- tAppendix: Events Impacting the Heroin Generation -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHeroin first reached Gejiu, a Chinese city in southern Yunnan known as Tin Capital, in the 1980s. Widespread use of the drug, which for a short period became "easier to buy than vegetables," coincided with radical changes in the local economy caused by the marketization of the mining industry. More than two decades later, both the heroin epidemic and the mining boom are often discussed as recent history. Middle-aged long-term heroin users, however, complain that they feel stuck in an earlier moment of the country's rapid reforms, navigating a world that no longer resembles either the tightly-knit Maoist work units of their childhood or the disorienting but opportunity-filled chaos of their early careers. Overcoming addiction in Gejiu has become inseparable from broader attempts to re-imagine laboring lives in a rapidly shifting social world. Drawing on more than eighteen months of fieldwork, Nicholas Bartlett explores how individuals' diverging experiences of recovery highlight shared challenges of inhabiting China's contested present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aDrug abusezChinazGejiuxHistory. 0aHeroin abusexSocial aspectszChinazGejiu. 0aRecovering addictsxEmploymentzChinazGejiu. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069041540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520975378zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520975378423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520975378.jpg  a978-3-11-069041-5  UC Press Frontlist eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070472-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2020  aZDB-23-SEWb2020